28.799999999999997px;"><strong>Going Private</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Overall, it=E2=80=99s true that auctions are do=
wn, but private deals seems
to be taking place at an impressive clip right now. Christie=E2=80=99s told=
 us in their year-end report that they had sold $1.5 billion worth of art p=
rivately, one of their best years for private sales ever. On Friday, I ment=
ioned the $130 million-plus sale of <strong>Valentino</strong>=E2=80=99s pr=
ized <strong>Basquiat</strong>, a prime example of the big deals excluded f=
rom the data sets that we tend to rely on to evaluate the market writ large=
=2E=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">And there=E2=80=99s lots more. Late last week, =
I spoke to a person who was working on a $20 million private deal=E2=80=94t=
his was mentioned casually, in passing. The week before, I spoke to someone=
 who believes the private market has legs beyond this transition period bec=
ause so many new buyers have entered the market in recent years, and becaus=
e sellers, including estates, have begun to see the advantages of selling p=
rivately.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Why are we in a phase of the m=
arket that favors private sales? There are many benefits having to do with =
flexibility and discretion. But the main reason is that the overall price l=
evel for the highest-value art has not changed much in recent years. Twenty=
 years ago, the contemporary art market began to take off. Now it dominates=
 the art world, galleries, the market, and museums. A decade ago, the marke=
t peaked. For the most part, no one needs a recent
auction price to convince a buyer that a work of art is valuable. Equally, =
sellers are somewhat anchored to prices they saw on the auction block in th=
e heyday of 2013-15. It=E2=80=99s not that prices haven=E2=80=99t changed s=
ince 2015; they go up and down, for sure. But they haven=E2=80=99t changed =
in <em>register</em>. Really crazy auction prices still fall below $200 mil=
lion, with the exception of that $450 million <strong>Leonardo</strong>.</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">If you can sell a rare <strong>Magritte</strong> for $1=
21 million at auction or an exceptional Basquiat for over $130 million priv=
ately, there=E2=80=99s a dozen good reasons to go the private route because=
 everyone knows top prices are possible, even plausible in some cases, eith=
er way. The same is true of works at every price point up and down the scal=
e. We=E2=80=99ve seen how large abstract paintings by <strong>Gerhard Richt=
er </strong>still trade publicly at roughly the same level as they
did when they were leading the market a dozen years ago. This may be the ke=
y point of the last five years of the market. The post-pandemic surge, espe=
cially the huge headlines for the $900 million <strong>Macklowe</strong> sa=
le and $1.6 billion <strong>Paul Allen</strong> sale, seemed to suggest tha=
t we were going to see another step up in the inexorable rise in prices. Ov=
er the last two years, we learned that the broader market wasn=E2=80=99t go=
ing to blindly follow those extraordinary collections into
the price stratosphere. Instead, we got a standoff between sellers and buye=
rs.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;">Until we see the numbers of highly traded works move to a=
 substantially elevated level, it=E2=80=99s easy for buyers and sellers to =
come to a fair price on the private market without the need for price disco=
very, which is the primary function of the public marketplace. So, just bec=
ause the higher end of the auction market is quiet doesn=E2=80=99t
mean the art market itself is dying, even if the data sometimes suggests ot=
herwise.=C2=A0</p></div>
